sentences.sentence: New year predictions The bookies have Labor being safely returned at the next election.

But there are problems ahead next year in population, the economy, housing, energy, health and education.The Albanese government finishes 2022 in rude good health in terms of public support, with opinion polls showing Labor's primary vote nudging slowly up towards 40 per cent and rising to the mid-50s after preferences.Almost two-thirds of Australians are satisfied Anthony Albanese is doing a good job and reckon he should stick around as prime minister.The other bloke, Peter Dutton, is still in the doghouse vacated by his predecessor, Scott ("it wasn't my fault") Morrison, with the Coalition vote frozen in the mid-30s, and with only one in four voters rating Dutton a better alternative for prime minister.On the eve of 2023, Labor is looking a bit of a shoo-in to win the 2025 federal election, with the bookies offering $4.50 to the minority of Tory diehards who think Dutton is the better man to displace Albanese from the Lodge.What could possibly go wrong for Albo in 2023?Let's start with the big kahuna: population growth.Since the microeconomic reforms of the Hawke-Keating era, Australian governments have relied on population growth to drive economic growth, limiting per capita gains for Australian workers.With Australian women waiting longer to have fewer kids, this has left the driver for population growth with younger migrants.
And COVID-19 border closures turned this tap off for two years.Some 110,000 net overseas migrants left Australia in the 18 months of peak lockdowns to September 2021.

In the two years to March 2022, Victoria and NSW lost almost 100,000 residents to Queensland, Western Australia, and South Australia.When compared with pre-COVID-19 population projections based on net overseas migration of about 240,000 a year, border closures and lockdowns took half a million people out of the Australian economy in the two years to March 2022.

Victoria, the lockdown state, lost a quarter of a million, NSW lost 150,000.In the quarter ended June 30 there was a recovery in net overseas migration, as soft visa sales resumed to overseas students, but this can't make up for the loss of 500,000 younger migrants in the two years of COVID-19 lockdowns, especially in the suburbs of inner Melbourne and Sydney, where these aspirational migrants would have gone on to the outer growth suburbs - to build homes, get jobs, start businesses, have kids and send them to school.Paradoxically, this short COVID-19 cohort of young migrants meant that the $300 billion stimulus spend from the Morrison government and the monetary stimulus from the Reserve Bank of Australia's 0.1 cash rate target was splurged on a smaller labour market, pulling the seasonally adjusted jobless rate down below the RBA's benchmark of 4 per cent by February 2022, just in time to increase interest rates on May 3, 2022, weeks before the federal election on May 21.The probability of this occurring was reported in The Australian on May 10, 2021.

With interest rates now at 3.1 per cent and rising, and overseas students flooding back into the country as fast as visas can be stamped, the reverse effect is likely to occur.In other words, tighter monetary policy will seem to produce higher unemployment rates than expected among an expanding supply of workers during the latter half of 2023.In 2023, one in four younger, aspirational migrants and swinging voters will find their 2020-21 fixed mortgage rates jumping from around 2 per cent to a variable rate of about 5 per cent or 6 per cent, as their homes decline in value by as much as 20 per cent and the value of their more speculative equity investments also begins to tank.Ouch.About this time, zombie companies addicted to cheap debt will begin to hit the wall, particularly in construction and among residential and commercial property developers, as Christopher Joye has written in The Australian Financial Review.To maintain affordable supplies of energy in the face of soaring international demand, the Commonwealth has legislated to give sweeping powers to Treasurer Jim Chalmers to control supply, demand and price in the gas market.The gas companies object to this vehemently on the basis that manipulating supply, demand and price is what they are normally allowed to do by compliant state governments.South Australia even bailed out local gas producer Santos when that pesky West Australian Alan Bond tried to take it over in the 1970s.

Now that really is Soviet state-style intervention.There are only two things that can be said here with any confidence about energy in 2023: prices for gas and electricity will both go up and, now that it has intervened, the Commonwealth will be blamed for it.The Australian primary health system, increasingly based on female, part-time, self-employed family doctors, has been getting starved of cash flow by deferrals and cuts to Medicare rebates, first by former Labor treasurer Wayne Swan in his last budget of 2013 and then by successive Coalition governments.As revenue falls below sustainable levels for family doctors, voters will find it increasingly difficult to obtain quality consultations and be instead forced to rely on corporatised, five-minute medicine and state public hospitals.
Once again, local federal MPs will cop the blame.

So they should, really.The failure of state school home learning during COVID-19 lockdowns pushed parents from the state school system, and the huge $300 billion COVID-19 stimulus meant many families, particularly if employed in the building and construction industries, could afford non-government school options in the Catholic or independent school sectors.In fact, the last Australian Bureau of Statistics school census showed not only plummeting year-on-year market share for state schools in 2021, but a drop in absolute numbers of students enrolled in state schools across the country, with many aspirational parents enrolling their children in Catholic and independent schools.ABS numbers for 2022 are not officially available, but the trend appears set to continue into 2023 and is likely to carry on in 2024.This trend is unlikely to worry the parents concerned, but it will definitely upset the public sector teachers' unions, who, along with the nurses' unions, are keeping the ACTU in pocket money now that union membership is down to 12.5 per cent.The advice I'd normally give a prime minister in these circumstances is to keep blaming Morrison.The bloke is hanging around parliament like the ghost of leaders past, and he was loathed by the better-paid voters who put Labor into office.My advice for Coalition MPs is to get used to losing, because with two Liberal National Party right-wingers from Queensland leading the outfit, an invisible shadow treasurer and the teals siphoning off your vote in wealthier seats, you're not going to win the next election, no matter how bad the economy looks.For the teals, please just accept that you represent better-paid Australians who got to be better paid by studying hard, and then by working harder.The ACTU hasn't made this illegal yet, although this is probably its next target after the Productivity Commission.John Black pioneered demographic and political profiling in Australia and is executive chairman of profiling company Australian Development Strategies.
He is a former Labor senator for Queensland.
